  "explanation": [
    {
      "heading": "JavaScript is Single-Threaded",
      "body": "JS runs on a single thread — only one thing executes at a time. The **call stack** tracks which function is currently executing.\n\nWhen you call a function, it's pushed onto the stack. When it returns, it's popped off.",
      "appearsAtStep": 0
    },
    {
      "heading": "Synchronous Execution",
      "body": "`console.log('start')` is synchronous — it runs immediately when the engine reaches it.\n\nIt's pushed onto the call stack, executes, and is immediately popped.",
      "appearsAtStep": 1
    },
    {
      "heading": "Web APIs Handle Async Work",
      "body": "`setTimeout` is not actually a JS feature — it's a **Web API** provided by the browser. When called, JS registers the callback with the browser and pops `setTimeout` off the stack immediately.\n\nJS doesn't wait — the browser handles the timer in the background.",
      "appearsAtStep": 3,
      "callout": "This is why setTimeout(fn, 0) doesn't mean \"run now\" — it means \"run after the current script finishes\"."
    },
    {
      "heading": "Microtasks vs Macrotasks",
      "body": "There are **two** task queues:\n- **Microtask queue**: Promise callbacks, `queueMicrotask()` — runs after every task, before the browser paints\n- **Callback queue (macrotask)**: `setTimeout`, `setInterval`, I/O events — runs one per event loop tick\n\nThe event loop always **drains all microtasks before taking one macrotask**.",
      "appearsAtStep": 5,
      "callout": "This is why Promise.then() always runs before setTimeout, even setTimeout(fn, 0)."
    },
    {
      "heading": "The Event Loop Tick",
      "body": "When the call stack is empty, the event loop:\n1. Runs **all** microtasks (until the microtask queue is empty)\n2. Takes **one** macrotask from the callback queue\n3. Renders any UI updates (browser only)\n4. Repeats",
      "appearsAtStep": 7
    },
    {
      "heading": "Execution Order Confirmed",
      "body": "Our code outputs:\n```\nstart\nend\nPromise callback  ← microtask\nsetTimeout callback  ← macrotask\n```\nThis holds true regardless of how long the timer delay is — even 0ms.",
      "appearsAtStep": 11
    }
  ],

